.TH _PRINTF 3 "APRIL 2026" "Holberton School" "Custom Printf Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.sp
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fB_printf\fP() function produces output according to a \fIformat\fP.
It writes output to \fBstdout\fP, the standard output stream.
.PP
This function writes output under the control of a \fIformat\fP string that specifies how subsequent arguments are converted for output. The format string is composed of zero or more directives: ordinary characters (not \fB%\fP), which are copied unchanged to the output stream; and conversion specifications, each of which results in fetching zero or more subsequent arguments.
.PP
If a conversion specification is invalid or not supported, the \fB%\fP character and the unrecognized character are both printed exactly as they appear in the format string.
.SS Conversion specifiers
A character that specifies the type of conversion to be applied. The conversion specifiers and their meanings are:
.TP
.B d, i
The \fBint\fP argument is converted to signed decimal notation. If the value is negative, a '\-' is printed first.
.TP
.B c
The \fBint\fP argument is converted to an \fBunsigned char\fP, and the resulting character is written.
.TP
.B s
The \fBchar *\fP argument is expected to be a pointer to an array of character type (pointer to a string). Characters from the array are written up to (but not including) a terminating null byte. If the pointer is NULL, it prints exactly "(null)".
.TP
.B %
A literal \fB%\fP is written. No argument is converted. The complete conversion specification is \fB%%\fP.
.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful return, the \fB_printf\fP() function returns the number of characters printed.
.PP
If the \fIformat\fP string is NULL, or if the format string ends abruptly after a \fB%\fP character, the function returns \-1.
